    <h1>A Neglected Argument for the Reality of God</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Charles Sanders Peirce · 1908 · <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/A_Neglected_Argument_for_the_Reality_of_God">Wikisource (public domain)</a><br/><em>Hibbert Journal</em>, 7(1), pp. 90–112.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-200/50 mb-2 font-bold italic">Editor's Summary</p>
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Musement is the free play of the mind. From it emerges the hypothesis of God's Reality. Peirce defines the three stages of inquiry: Retroduction (Abduction), Deduction, and Induction. The "Neglected Argument" is the first stage of a scientific inquiry.</p>
    </div>

